{{Infobox Artwork | image_file=Correggio,_martirio_dei_quattro_santi.jpg | image_size= 380px | title=Martyrdom of Four Saints | artist=[[Antonio Allegri|Correggio]] | year=c. 1524 | medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | height_metric=160 | width_metric=185 | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | museum=[[Galleria Nazionale di Parma|Galleria Nazionale]], [[Parma]] }}
The '''''Martyrdom of Four Saints''''' is an [[oil painting|oil on canvas]] painting by the Italian Renaissance artist [[Antonio Allegri|Correggio]], dating from around 1524 and housed in the [[Galleria Nazionale di Parma|Galleria Nazionale]] of [[Parma]], [[Italy]].
==History== The work is one of the canvasses commissioned by Parmesan noble Placido Del Bono for a chapel in the church of [[San Giovanni Evangelista, Parma|San Giovanni Evangelista]] in Parma. They are mentioned (although wrongly assigned to the [[Parma Cathedral|city's cathedral]]) by late Renaissance art biographer [[Giorgio Vasari]] in the first edition of his ''Lives'' (1550).
The subject of the painting, rather rare in western religious art, is the martyrdom of [[Placidus (martyr)|Placidus]] and his sister Flavia (who had allegedly lived in the 4th century) and, behind them, that of two earlier Roman siblings, Eutychius and Victorinus, who appear to have been already beheaded. An angel flies above them and holds the palm of martyrdom.
==Sources== *{{cite book|last= Adani|first=Giuseppe|year=2007|title=Correggio pittore universale|location=[[Correggio, Emilia-Romagna|Correggio]]|publisher=Silvana Editoriale}} {{commons category|Martyrdom of four saint}}
