[[File:Victorian Artists' Society Melbourne.jpg|thumb|The Victorian Artists' Society building]] The '''Victorian Artists Society''', which can trace its establishment to 1856 in [[Melbourne]], promotes artistic education, art classes and gallery hire [[art gallery|exhibition]] in Australia.
The Victorian Artists Society was formed in March 1888 following the decision of the Victorian Academy of Arts and the Australian Artists' Association to amalgamate.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article6109757 |title=VICTORIAN ACADEMY OF ARTS. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=14 March 1888 |accessdate=20 September 2013 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The Victorian Academy of Arts had been formed in 1870 with 'about twenty artists and amateurs' amongst its first members.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13199253 |title=OUR MELBOURNE LETTER. |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=22 January 1870 |accessdate=20 September 2013 |page=7 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The Academy's forerunner, the Victorian Society of Fine Arts, was established in 1856.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article71468655 |title=HISTORIC MELBOURNE. |newspaper=[[Australian Town and Country Journal]] |location=NSW |date=22 June 1901 |accessdate=20 September 2013 |page=30 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The Australian Artists' Association held its first exhibition in 1886 with works by [[Tom Roberts]], [[Louis Buvelot]], [[Frederick McCubbin]], and [[Arthur Streeton]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11571934 |title=EXHIBITION OF THE AUSTRALIAN ARTISTS' ASSOCIATION. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=7 September 1886 |accessdate=20 September 2013 |page=7 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>
The founding president of the new amalgamated Society was Joseph Anderson Panton<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article89950234 |title=DEATH OF MR. J. A. PANTON. |newspaper=[[Bendigo Advertiser]] |location=Vic. |date=27 October 1913 |accessdate=20 September 2013 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and later presidents included [[Frederick McCubbin]] and [[Paul Raphael Montford]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article4396813 |title=IN A SCULPTOR'S STUDIO. |newspaper=[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]] |location=Melbourne |date=5 May 1931 |accessdate=20 September 2013 |page=5 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>
The premises at 430 Albert Street in East Melbourne were erected for the society in 1888, enlarged in 1892 and modernised in 1953. Facilities include four galleries, teaching studio, members room, offices and other ancillary facilities.
Membership is restricted to 1000, a figure last reached in 1979, and is open for new members to join. Membership is open to all persons interested in the fine arts, with the emphasis on practising artists.
Regular classes are held in various media which are open to members and non-members including watercolour, oil painting, drawing, mixed media, life model.
Exhibitions are held annually, including the seasonal spring, summer, autumn and winter exhibitions, with awards given at each.
The 2017 Artist of the Year Award was given to Ray Hewitt.
